<h1 id="4">4</h1>

<p>Some people think that it is preferable for young people to choose a different type of job than their parents did.<br />
However, in my opinion, young people have more advantages if they work in the same field as their parents since they can get helpful advice from their parents and they can utilize their parentsâ€™ professional contacts.</p>

<p>To begin with, young workers can receive useful advice from their parents when they share the same career.<br />
Parents have gained a lot of knowledge about their jobs due to extensive work experience, and thus they can provide valuable direction.<br />
For example, my friend became an elementary school teacher like her parents.<br />
When she began teaching, things were really overwhelming at first.<br />
She had a hard time managing her studentsâ€™ behavior, and she was not sure of the best way to solve the problem.<br />
However, her parents were able to give her a lot of useful tips on how to manage her students.<br />
They suggested that she set clear rules and enforce them consistently, and she implemented her parentsâ€™ advice right away.<br />
Consequently, her studentsâ€™ behavior improved dramatically.</p>

<p>On top of that, young people can make use of their parentsâ€™ professional connections when they work in the same field.<br />
In particular, young workers can utilize their parentsâ€™ work-related contacts to create useful business partnerships.<br />
Take the example of Bill Gates, who chose a career in business like his mother.<br />
His first noteworthy success was when IBM hired his company, Microsoft, to develop software for IBMâ€™s computers.<br />
This happened because Bill Gatesâ€™ mother had a professional connection with one of IBMâ€™s directors.<br />
She told the IBM board member about Microsoft, and as a result, Bill Gatesâ€™ company could develop a partnership with IBM.</p>

<p>To sum up, young people who pursue the same career that their parents did can get invaluable guidance from their parents and benefit from their parentsâ€™ work-related contacts.<br />
In this regard, I argue that it is advisable for young people to follow in their parentsâ€™ career footsteps rather than select a different occupation for themselves.</p>

