<h1 id="5">5</h1>

<p>The lecturer argues that attracting new businesses with incentives can have drawbacks.<br />
This contradicts the reading passageâ€™s claim that luring new businesses with incentives is a great idea.</p>

<p>First, the lecturer maintains that it doesnâ€™t add money for local investment.<br />
A university study found that overall tax revenue was reduced.<br />
Companies receive tax rebates as incentives, so tax revenue does not increase.<br />
This casts doubt on the reading passageâ€™s claim that attracting new businesses with incentives generates more tax revenue for local investment.</p>

<p>Next, the lecturer asserts that it does not provide more jobs for local people.<br />
The new businesses will compete with existing ones, which means that some existing jobs will be lost.<br />
In addition, the new companies will probably bring their own employees to the new area, so local residents will not get the new jobs.<br />
This counters the reading passageâ€™s claim that giving incentives to companies will create jobs for locals.</p>

<p>Finally, the lecturer argues that it doesnâ€™t help to local environment.<br />
In fact, pollution will increase locally when any new business is added to a region.<br />
This is because even a green factory generates a small amount of pollution.<br />
This refutes the reading passageâ€™s claim that using incentives to attract new businesses will benefit the local environment.</p>

